comments.commentBody:
@Digital:<br/>
From your post I gather you aren't one of those in the know either.<br/>
We know that Medicare spending is reduced from future budgets, but we also read everywhere that Medicare can't continue in the present form. And no one seems interested in fixing it expect House Republicans. <br/><br/>You quote numbers, but with due respect, I rather hear the real debate by those in the know which excludes comments, TV pundits of all stripes, and media columnists. The later have an ax to grind. And I know that with enough money you can hire financial experts to give a spin on numbers to reach almost any conclusion you like. Cherry picking little pieces like you did doesn't make a case, and useless to rebut one by one. I rather hear the entire argument against Ryan laid out in an orderly manner (I suggested House floor), and then challenged, again in an orderly manner, by liberal representative(s) who live and breathe this stuff. <br/><br/>I am willing to be humble and admit I don't know enough details of entitlement structures for precise discussion. Certainly not in short space such as here. Won't you admit the same?? And advocate such  an orderly debate? Otherwise people will simply have to decide whom to believe without hearing the arguments in depth: will they trust Ryan or the liberal media? <br/><br/>In case you think such argument has already been made, it was Ryan who argued fast and hard against Obamacare during its birth, and the people decided to believe him in 2010.
